## Explanation:

### Solution 01

- Using ***Recursive & Backtracking.***
- As we have to take elements from 1 to n, first we’re passing 1 for the first time to our recursive function.
- Base case will be when the temp size will be equal to k, we’ll push to ans and return it.
- Else we’ll iterate with a loop till current number to n & make a recursive call for next numbers.
- Also after the function comes back we’ve to remove the element from temp and continue the loop.
- **Time complexity:** O((nCk)*k), where nCk is all possible subsets and k to copy subsets into ans vector.
- **Space complexity:** O((nCk)*k), to store all n C k subset in the ans vector of size k.

### Solution 02

- Using ***Iterative Approach.***
- Here we have 3 test cases:
    1. `if(temp[itr] > n)` Here, temp array at the itr position is exhausted. So there is no possible value that can be inserted at this position anymore. Since we started with the temp being filled with all zeros and incremented it step by step, we must have already passed all possible values for that index. In this case, we step back to one index and see if we can still increase the one element at the index behind.
    2. `if(itr == k-1)` Here, we have reached the end of our possible combination. Each of our combinations has a max length of k, so it doesn't make sense to look at arrays that are larger than that. At this point, we can just add to our final result whichever value we've found.
    3. `else` we are in a scenario where both 1. and 2. are not satisfied. This means that our temp array at the itr position is NOT exhausted and we are NOT at the end of our array. In this case, we fix the value at itr and step one index ahead and start increasing the value at itr+1. We also copy the value of itr to itr+1 because to avoid duplications we make sure that our array always maintains the property that it is sorted in increasing order.

